surveys.narrative: Barbour Lake is 51 acres in size and is located just south of Garrison in eastern Crow Wing County. It is connected to the much larger Smith Lake by navigable channel. There were five homes/cabins along the 1.0 miles of shoreline in 1997. There was no designated public access present.The lake is 54 feet deep and about 25% of the surface area is less than 15 feet deep. It is a hardwater lake with moderate phosphorus fertility. Water clarity was above average for the area in 1997. Bottom soils in water less than four feet deep are primarily muck and marl. The aquatic plant community is fairly diverse. Emergent species help cycle nutrients and buffer shorelines from excessive wave damage. Species like bulrush and wild rice often enhance the quality of spawning habitat for a variety of fish species, but are generally absent from Barbour Lake. Submergent and floating leafed species provide important cover and food resources for a wide variety of aquatic life.The 1997 test netting showed a varied fish population. Northern pike numbers were "low" when compared to similar type lakes but pike averaged 32 inches and over 8 lbs. in size. The catch rate was similar to that from adjoining Smith Lake. Walleyes were not sampled but were caught in "low" numbers in Smith Lake. The largemouth bass catch was in the "average" category and several age classes were present. Bluegill catch was also "average" and about 20% were 7.0 inches or more in length. Other panfish caught at "average" rates included pumpkinseeds and rock bass.Yellow perch and tullibees are important forage fish for the lake's gamefish species. Yellow perch were only sampled as young fish in Barbour and were caught in "low" numbers in Smith Lake. Tullibees were caught in "high" numbers, however. Other species sampled in '97 included bowfin (dogfish) and yellow bullhead, both taken in "low" numbers in test nets.

Barbour Lake is a 56 acre lake which can be accessed through a channel from Smith Lake. Tullibee (Cisco) was the most abundant species sampled at 69.5/ gill net. Average length was 10.7". Northern Pike are not very abundant but can be nice sized. The two Northern Pike sampled averaged 31.3". Black Crappies were sampled in average numbers at 1.0/ trap net when compared to similar lakes. Average length was 9.3", with 75% at least 8.0" in length. Bluegill were also sampled in average numbers at 8.5/ trap net. Average length was 6.1", with 29% at least 7.0" in length.

Barbour Lake can only be accessed by boat through a channel from Smith Lake. The two most abundant species netted were bluegill and tullibee (cisco). Bluegill were captured at the rate of 25.8/net. Average length was only 5.2" and only 6% were 7" or longer. The tullibee (cisco) average length was 11.3".

Other fish species sampled included black crappie, bowfin (dogfish), green sunfish, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass, pumpkinseed, yellow bullhead, and yellow perch. Various minnow species were also captured while backpack electrofishing, including central mudminnows and a pugnose shiner.

Test netting does not indicate large populations of any fish. However the nature of the drop-off and the dense weed growth hampered the setting of nets and thus the figures obtained may not be representative of the lake. The bluegill population appears to be adequate with a good black crappie population. Largemouth bass and northern pike are present in fair numbers.

A temperature-dissolved oxygen profile was collected in the deepest basin on Barbour Lake on August 16, 2023, to evaluate the amount of cold, oxygenated water (i.e., oxythermal habitat) available to Cisco, also known as Tullibee. Based on the profile, the top of the thermocline (i.e., the location in the water column with the sharpest transition from warm to cold water) occurred at approximately 13 feet. Dissolved oxygen decreased to below 3.0 mg/L at 24.7 feet, which was within the thermocline, at the time of sampling. The temperature at which dissolved oxygen decreased to below 3.0 mg/L (i.e., TDO3, a single variable to characterize oxythermal habitat) was 8.3?C (46.9?F).

TDO3 values cooler than 21.5?C indicate that oxythermal conditions are favorable for Cisco. Dissolved oxygen concentrations within the thermocline indicate that suitable oxythermal habitat for Cisco was available across a range of depths at the time of sampling during the summer of 2023. Data collected in 1974-2010 further indicate suitable oxythermal habitat across years, with the least favorable conditions recorded in 2010. When inadequate oxythermal habitat is available, Cisco are squeezed into unfavorable, warmer water conditions and therefore experience higher levels of stress.
